                        <section class="pmc-journal-banner text-center line-height-none" aria-label="Journal banner"><img src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/banners/logo-procamia.gif" alt="AMIA Annual Symposium Proceedings logo" usemap="#pmc-banner-imagemap" width="500" height="75"><map name="pmc-banner-imagemap"><area alt="Link to AMIA Annual Symposium Proceedings" title="Link to AMIA Annual Symposium Proceedings" shape="default" href="https://knowledge.amia.org/all-proceedings" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"></map></section><article lang="en"><section aria-label="Article citation and metadata"><section class="pmc-layout__citation font-secondary font-xs"><div>
<div class="display-inline-block"><button type="button" class="cursor-pointer text-no-underline bg-transparent border-0 padding-0 text-left margin-0 text-normal text-primary" aria-controls="journal_context_menu">AMIA Annu Symp Proc</button></div>. 2018 Dec 5;2018:490–497.</div>
<nav id="journal_context_menu" hidden="hidden"><ul class="menu-list font-family-ui" role="menu">
<li role="presentation"><a href='https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/search/?term="AMIA%20Annu%20Symp%20Proc"[jour]' class="usa-link" role="menuitem">Search in PMC</a></li>
<li role="presentation"><a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="AMIA%20Annu%20Symp%20Proc"[jour]' lang="en" class="usa-link" role="menuitem">Search in PubMed</a></li>
<li role="presentation"><a href='https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nlmcatalog?term="AMIA%20Annu%20Symp%20Proc"[Title%20Abbreviation]' class="usa-link" role="menuitem">View in NLM Catalog</a></li>
<li role="presentation"><a href='?term="AMIA%20Annu%20Symp%20Proc"[jour]' class="usa-link" role="menuitem" data-add-to-search="true">Add to search</a></li>
</ul></nav></section><section class="front-matter"><div class="ameta p font-secondary font-xs">
<hgroup><h1>Analysis of Total Time Requirements of Electronic Health Record Use by Ophthalmologists Using Secondary EHR Data</h1></hgroup><div class="cg p">
<a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Goldstein%20IH"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id1"><span class="name western">Isaac H Goldstein</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id1">
<h3><span class="name western">Isaac H Goldstein</span></h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Medical Informatics &amp; Clinical Epidemiology</div>
<div class="p">
<sup>2</sup>Ophthalmology Oregon Health &amp; Science University, Portland, OR</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Goldstein%20IH"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Isaac H Goldstein</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1,</sup><sup>2</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Hribar%20MR"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id2"><span class="name western">Michelle R Hribar</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id2">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Michelle R Hribar</span>, <span class="degrees">PhD</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Medical Informatics &amp; Clinical Epidemiology</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Hribar%20MR"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Michelle R Hribar</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Reznick%20LG"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id3"><span class="name western">Leah G Reznick</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id3">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Leah G Reznick</span>, <span class="degrees">MD</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>2</sup>Ophthalmology Oregon Health &amp; Science University, Portland, OR</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Reznick%20LG"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Leah G Reznick</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>2</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Chiang%20MF"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id4"><span class="name western">Michael F Chiang</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id4">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Michael F Chiang</span>, <span class="degrees">MD, MA</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Medical Informatics &amp; Clinical Epidemiology</div>
<div class="p">
<sup>2</sup>Ophthalmology Oregon Health &amp; Science University, Portland, OR</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Chiang%20MF"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Michael F Chiang</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1,</sup><sup>2</sup>
</div>
<ul class="d-buttons inline-list">
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="aip_a" aria-expanded="false">Author information</button></li>
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="anp_a" aria-expanded="false">Article notes</button></li>
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="clp_a" aria-expanded="false">Copyright and License information</button></li>
</ul>
<div class="d-panels font-secondary-light">
<div id="aip_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none">
<div class="p" id="af1-2976958">
<sup>1</sup>Medical Informatics &amp; Clinical Epidemiology</div>
<div id="af2-2976958">
<sup>2</sup>Ophthalmology Oregon Health &amp; Science University, Portland, OR</div>
</div>
<div id="anp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="notes p"><section id="historyarticle-meta1" class="history"><p>Collection date 2018.</p></section></div></div>
<div id="clp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none">
<div>©2018 AMIA - All rights reserved.</div>
<p>This is an Open Access article: verbatim copying and redistribution of this article are permitted in all media for any purpose</p>
<div class="p"><a href="/about/copyright/" class="usa-link">PMC Copyright notice</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<div>PMCID: PMC6371357  PMID: <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30815089/" class="usa-link">30815089</a>
</div>
</div></section></section><section aria-label="Article content"><section class="body main-article-body"><section class="abstract" id="abstract1"><h2>Abstract</h2>
<p>Electronic Health Records (EHRs) are widely used in the United States for clinical care and billing activities. Their widespread adoption has raised a variety of concerns about their effects on providers and medical care. As researchers address these concerns, they will need to understand how much time providers actually spend on the EHR. This study develops and validates methods for calculating total time requirements for EHR use by ophthalmologists using secondary EHR data from audit logs. Key findings from this study are that (1) Secondary EHR data can be used to estimate lower bounds on provider EHR use, (2) Providers spend a large amount of time using the EHR, (3) Most time spent on the EHR is spent reviewing information. These findings have important implications for practicing clinicians, and for EHR system design in the future.</p></section><section id="sec1"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Introduction</h2>
<p>Electronic Health Records (EHRs) have been adopted rapidly throughout the United States, with 74% of physicians using EHRs in 2014, and are now tied to provider reimbursement.<sup><a href="#r1-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r1-2976958">1</a>,<a href="#r2-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r2-2976958">2</a></sup> However, EHR adoption has been accompanied by some concerns about potential negative impact on factors such as financial success, clinical efficiency, provider burnout, provider cognition, communication with patients, and data accuracy.<sup><a href="#r3-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r3-2976958">3</a>–<a href="#r8-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r8-2976958">8</a></sup> With EHRs now commonplace, methods for addressing these concerns are increasingly needed.</p>
<p>An important dimension in this process is to understand how much time providers actually spend using the EHR. In a previous study, we used EHR audit logs to estimate that ophthalmologists spent 3.7 hours per day using the EHR for office visits. Other studies using audit logs have estimated total EHR use in other specialties as being between 3 to 6 hours per day.<sup><a href="#r9-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r9-2976958">9</a>–<a href="#r11-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r11-2976958">11</a></sup> Time and motion and self-reported studies also show that providers spend significant time using the EHR, resulting in decreased productivity.<sup><a href="#r12-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r12-2976958">12</a>–<a href="#r14-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r14-2976958">14</a></sup> While other studies have used audit logs to estimate total EHR usage, these audit log studies have either used unclear or unvalidated methodologies.<sup><a href="#r10-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r10-2976958">10</a>,<a href="#r11-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r11-2976958">11</a></sup> Furthermore, most other studies have focused on documentation time alone. Knowing the total time requirements for EHR use is an important gap in knowledge because EHRs have become more prominent in healthcare as information repositories and holistic communication tools for health care providers. Federal regulations have increasingly promoted EHR use for purposes such as patient communication and documentation for new value-based purchasing paradigms.<sup><a href="#r2-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r2-2976958">2</a></sup></p>
<p>During the past several years, we have developed and validated methods for using EHR audit logs to assess clinical workflow.<sup><a href="#r9-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r9-2976958">9</a>,<a href="#r15-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r15-2976958">15</a>–<a href="#r17-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r17-2976958">17</a></sup> The purpose of our current study is to build on previously published work by estimating the time ophthalmologists spent on all activities in the EHR, as well as the time spent reviewing versus documenting in the EHR. This will provide additional insight into how providers use the EHR, and where improvements in the EHR may have the most impact. As ophthalmology is a high-volume specialty with a mix of surgical and outpatient visits that relies on a combination of numeric, written, and photographed information, it is a useful specialty to study and draw conclusions that may be generalizable to other fields.</p></section><section id="sec2"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Methods</h2>
<p>This study was approved by the Institutional Review Board at Oregon Health &amp; Science University (OHSU).</p>
<section id="sec2_1"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Study Institution and Department</h3>
<p>Oregon Health and Science University (OHSU) is a large academic medical center located in Portland, Oregon. More than 50 attending providers perform over 115,000 outpatient exams annually in the department of ophthalmology. The department provides primary eye care and also serves as a tertiary referral center for the Pacific Northwest and nationally. The department adopted its current EHR in 2006, with a vendor that is a market share leader among large hospitals (EpicCare; Epic Systems, Verona, WI).<sup><a href="#r18-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r18-2976958">18</a></sup> Ambulatory practice management, documentation, order entry, medication prescribing, operating room management, and billing tasks are completed using the EHR. Providers also use the EHR to send and receive messages from both patients and staff.</p></section><section id="sec2_2"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">EHR Timing Data</h3>
<p>The time period of this study was January 1, 2016 to December 31 2016. Ophthalmology providers were excluded if they did not see patients in both January and February as well as November and December of 2016, or if they saw fewer than 200 patients in 2016. These criteria were chosen to minimize bias from providers with growing or shrinking practices, and for those providers not regularly seeing patients.</p>
<p>Provider audit logs and office visit data were gathered via OHSU’s clinical data warehouse (EpicCare; Epic Systems, Verona, WI). Audit log data used in this study included time stamps, audit log metric names and long descriptions (activity descriptors), associated encounter and patient IDs, associated encounter types (such as office visit or telephone call), and activity type (such as modify or review). For encounters, scheduled visit time, check in, checkout, encounter ID, patient ID, after visit summary print time and encounter close time were used. When encounter timing data was missing, the following substitutions were made:</p>
<ul class="list" style="list-style-type:disc">
<li><p>If check in times were missing, the scheduled visit time was used.</p></li>
<li><p>If checkout times were missing, the after visit summary print time was used.</p></li>
<li><p>If the after visit summary print time was missing, 8 hours after the encounter check in time was used.</p></li>
<li><p>If the encounter close time was missing, the minimum of the last recorded timestamp for that encounter or 48 hours after the encounter’s first timestamp was used.</p></li>
</ul></section><section id="sec2_3"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Calculating Total EHR Use Time</h3>
<p>Based on previously published methods,<sup><a href="#r9-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r9-2976958">9</a></sup> we calculated a provider’s total EHR use time as the number of distinct recorded minutes in their audit log for 2016. The presented metric (EHR hours per day) was calculated as the EHR time per office visit multiplied by the median number of office visits they saw in a given day. For example: Dr. Smith had 500,000 audit logs in her record for 2016. Of those 500,000, there were 172,000 unique minutes recorded. Her total EHR use time was estimated at 172,000 minutes or 286.7 hours. She saw 2,000 patients, and a median of 30 patients per clinic day, so her estimated EHR hours per day was 286.7 divided by 2000 multiplied by 30, which equals 4.3 hours per day.</p>
<p>Timestamps were split into two categories: <em>Patient Care</em> and <em>Other. Patient Care</em> timestamps consisted of timestamps associated with an encounter ID number or a patient ID number. <em>Other</em> timestamps were associated with neither an encounter ID number nor a patient ID number.</p>
<section id="sec2_3_1"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">Patient Care Timestamps</h4>
<p>For this category, timestamps were further subcategorized into 4 subcategories. The first three, <em>Pre-clinic, With Patient</em>, and <em>After Patient</em>, refer to work in the EHR for an open office visit encounter that occurred in preparation before the visit, while the patient was in clinic, and after the patient left clinic up until the encounter was closed. The fourth subcategory, <em>Patient Care Other</em>, refers to work done in the EHR for patients without open office visit encounters (e.g. phone calls or messages). The first three categories include audit log timestamps for open office visit encounters with the patient’s ID that occurred between 24 hours prior to the check in time and the encounter close time. <em>Pre-clinic</em> stamps were recorded between 24 hours prior to the check in time. <em>With Patient</em> timestamps were recorded between the check in and checkout times. <em>After Patient</em> were recorded between the checkout time and the encounter close time. <em>Patient Care Other</em> timestamps either were not associated with office visits, or were recorded outside of the time window of the other three categories.</p></section><section id="sec2_3_2"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">Other Timestamps</h4>
<p>Timestamps in this category were subcategorized according to their metric names and description as <em>Dashboard, System Response, Internal Messaging</em>, and <em>Other. Dashboard</em> refers to the provider’s homepage which may display a summary of the days schedule or the contents of their internal message inbox. <em>System Response</em> refers to timestamps related to logging in and out and accessing restricted data. <em>Messaging</em> refers to timestamps related to the EHR's messaging system which were not associated with a patient or encounter ID. <em>Other</em> refers to timestamps not easily categorized, as well as timestamps related to patient records that lacked patient IDs.</p></section></section><section id="sec2_4"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Calculating EHR Time for Subcategories</h3>
<p>For each recorded minute of EHR use, the minute was divided proportionally into each subcategory based on the number of timestamps of a subcategory recorded in that minute. This allowed us to split our total EHR use time calculation into the different kinds of EHR use time. Finally, using a field provided by the vendor, we also distinguished between timestamps that represented modifying new information in the EHR, versus reviewing information already present in the EHR.</p></section><section id="sec2_5"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Validation</h3>
<p>In a previous study, we validated similar methods for estimating the time providers spent documenting office visits by examining time spent by providers documenting when patients were present.<sup><a href="#r9-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r9-2976958">9</a></sup> Validation of methods developed for this study was based on calculations of the times when providers were not with patients. To this end, one pediatric ophthalmology provider (LR) was asked to log her EHR time use while not in the clinic. For each recorded time interval, we then used the resulting audit logs to calculate the time spent on the EHR and compared the two values.</p></section><section id="sec2_6"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Analysis</h3>
<p>Processing of data, creation of statistics and p-values from paired t tests was conducted in R.<sup><a href="#r19-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r19-2976958">19</a></sup> Significance was defined as p&lt;.05.</p></section></section><section id="sec3"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Results</h2>
<section id="sec3_1"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Overview of Providers</h3>
<p><strong><a href="#t1-2976958" class="usa-link">Table 1</a></strong> provides summary data for the 48 ophthalmology department providers who met inclusion criteria for this study. 19 (40%) of providers were female, and the median provider age was 42 years. The most common subspecialty represented was Comprehensive Ophthalmology (n=10) followed by Retina (n=7). Two providers had dual subspecialties, and were not considered when analyzing results by sub-specialty, though they were included in overall results.</p>
