<div class="tw-foot p"><div class="fn" id="_fn_p45"><p><strong><a href="#t3-2976958" class="usa-link">Table 3</a>:</strong> Mean hours of EHR use per clinic day is calculated as a function of yearly EHR time, total office visits, and median visits per clinic day. Patient Care time is associated with either encounter IDs or patient IDs, Other time is not.</p></div></div></section><p>On average providers spent 4.3 ± 1.3 hours per clinic day using the electronic health record, ranging from 3.1 hours per clinic day to 5.9 ± .8 hours per clinic day for each specialty. Overall, 80% of this time was directly related to patient care. While the actual time varied between specialties, the percent of time spent on the <em>Patient Care</em> category was much less variable ranging from 73.1 ± 5.2 % to 89.4 ± 4.5 %.</p></section><section id="sec3_4"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Patient Care EHR Use</h3>
<p><strong><a href="#t4-2976958" class="usa-link">Table 4</a></strong> shows the breakdown for <em>Patient Care</em> time, both by timing categories and activity categories. On average, most <em>Patient Care</em> time is concerned with office visit encounters, with the largest portion spent when patients are actually present.</p>
<section class="tw xbox font-sm" id="t4-2976958"><h4 class="obj_head">Table 4.</h4>
<div class="caption p"><p>Patient Care Time Allocation</p></div>
<div class="tbl-box p" tabindex="0"><table class="content" frame="box" rules="none">
