<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/t5-2976958/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<div class="tw-foot p"><div class="fn" id="_fn_p49"><p><strong><a href="#t5-2976958" class="usa-link">Table 5</a>:</strong> The categories listed represent all types of Other activity. Minutes per Clinic Day is calculated the same as Hours per Clinic Day, with different units. Time is split further into activity type.</p></div></div></section></section></section><section id="sec4"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Discussion</h2>
<p>This study had three key findings: (1) EHR audit logs can be used to estimate lower bounds on provider EHR use time, (2) Providers spend a large amount of time using the EHR, (3) Most time spent on the EHR is spent reviewing information.</p>
<p>Key finding 1 from this study is that audit logs can be used to estimate lower bounds on provider EHR use time. In fact, when attempting to validate our results we found there were significant differences between the reported time spent using the EHR and the time calculated from audit logs <strong>(<a href="#t2-2976958" class="usa-link">Table 2</a>)</strong>. In the vast majority of cases, the calculated time underestimated the reported time. Upon further investigation, this was due to two main reasons, gaps in the audit log where no time stamps were recorded, and inaccurate interval end times. After reviewing the logs in detail, it was apparent that the main reason for gaps in the audit log were due to the provider writing clinical notes. When a user remains on a single screen of the EHR writing a note or reading a long message, no additional time stamps are generated until they move to the next screen, and our method underestimates the amount of time the user spent on that activity. Other reasons for these gaps included the reading or writing of messages and the viewing of ophthalmic images outside OHSU’s EHR. Some gaps could not be easily explained and may simply reflect the provider not using the computer during that time interval. This suggests that our method is most accurate when the provider is actively navigating through the EHR and least accurate when the provider is modifying the EHR. Overall, our method seems to be an underestimate of the time providers spend on the EHR.</p>
<p>Previous studies have estimated EHR use with with a variety of methods such as time motion studies or use of self-reported data, but such studies can be time and resource intensive.<sup><a href="#r12-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r12-2976958">12</a>,<a href="#r13-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r13-2976958">13</a></sup> Audit logs provide a potential way to capture all EHR activity on a broader scale. While other studies have used audit logs to calculate the time spent on the EHR, their methods are not always validated or clearly described.<sup><a href="#r10-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r10-2976958">10</a>,<a href="#r11-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r11-2976958">11</a></sup> Tai-Seale et. al clearly described their method of calculating activity time blocks whose start and end are determined by audit logs, and validated their approach for estimating face to face time with patients, but did not validate their approach for other activities.<sup><a href="#r10-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r10-2976958">10</a></sup> Arndt et. al validated their approach with a time motion study, but do not describe how they calculated EHR time using the audit logs, an important detail given there are at least two approaches.<sup><a href="#r9-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r9-2976958">9</a>–<a href="#r11-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r11-2976958">11</a></sup> Our study is complementary to their work by providing a clear methodology for estimating EHR use time, with preliminary evidence that our method calculates an underestimate. With EHRs now commonplace, and concerns about their use unresolved, having a method for hospitals and practices to estimate their EHR use time may be valuable for assessing impacts of changes to workflows, interfaces and policies. Utilizing audit logs seems like a cost effective method for doing so. Our results highlight the importance of validation to understand whether estimating with audit logs will over or under estimate actual use. Additional validation and new methodologies may be called for to confirm this finding and better estimate provider modification time.</p>
<p>Key finding 2 is that providers spend a large amount of time on the EHR. We calculated providers spent on average at least 4.3 ± 1.2 hours each clinic day. The vast majority of this time was spent on work directly related to patient care, and open encounters in particular <strong>(<a href="#t3-2976958" class="usa-link">Tables 3</a> &amp; <a href="#t4-2976958" class="usa-link">4</a>)</strong>. Our study is in line with other studies that show providers spend a large amount of time on the EHR, though our study reports noticeably less time than others.<sup><a href="#r10-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r10-2976958">10</a>,<a href="#r11-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r11-2976958">11</a></sup> This may be due to the underestimation inherent in our technique, but may also be related to the study cohort. This is the first study to our knowledge to estimate the total amount of time Ophthalmologists spend on the EHR. In a previous study, we estimated providers spent 3.7 hours a day on office visits, which is consistent with the time we estimate in this study for patient care activities in the EHR. <sup><a href="#r9-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r9-2976958">9</a></sup> By using the whole audit log, this study builds on the previous study by estimating all EHR activity, and highlights that providers spend a lot of time on activities not related to open office visits. In fact, we found nearly an hour of use each day could not be tied to work related to a particular patient <strong>(<a href="#t3-2976958" class="usa-link">Table 3</a>)</strong>. Most of this time was spent on the provider’s dashboard, which often displays information about multiple patients at once, such as the day’s schedule, or summaries of hospitalized patients <strong>(<a href="#t5-2976958" class="usa-link">Table 5</a>)</strong>. This finding may provide insight into provider usage patterns, suggesting providers not only use the EHR as a means to record information for individual patients, but as a means to manage many patients under their care at once. It also suggest providers spend large amounts of time on activities that cannot be directly billed for, which suggest changes in provider reimbursement policies may warrant consideration, as has been suggested by previous studies.<sup><a href="#r10-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r10-2976958">10</a>,<a href="#r11-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r11-2976958">11</a></sup></p>
<p>Other studies have raised concerns about how the use of EHRs affects providers, including their cognition, communication, and burnout rates.<sup><a href="#r5-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r5-2976958">5</a>–<a href="#r7-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r7-2976958">7</a>,<a href="#r20-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r20-2976958">20</a></sup> It seems likely these effects are related to the amount of time providers spend on the EHR. Though we found providers spent notable amounts of time on the EHR on work that could not be directly tied to patient care, still the majority of time spent on the EHR was associated with work on open outpatient office visits <strong>(<a href="#t4-2976958" class="usa-link">Table 4</a>)</strong>. As researchers and designers attempt to improve the efficiency of time spent on EHRs, our results suggest focus might be placed on minimizing time spent on work related to open office visits, where reforms will have the most impact on overall EHR use time. Future work might also include investigating the workflows behind the different categories of EHR us, as well as ways to optimize those workflows.</p>
<p>The final key finding of this study is that providers appear to spend much of their time on the EHR reviewing information. Providers spent approximately 4 hours a day reviewing information in the EHR, the vast majority of the time estimated using the EHR. In every subcategory of EHR time but one, the majority of time was spent reviewing information. Whether working on office visits or other encounters or tasks not related to patients, providers are usually reviewing information.</p>
<p>We note that our method of calculating EHR use time underestimates the amount of time spent writing clinical notes or in basket messages by a factor of, on average, 2.9 ± 2.6 by our validation. A rough approximation suggests there is an additional 50 minutes of modifying activity in the EHR; nevertheless, reviewing information in the EHR is how providers spend most of their time.</p>
<p>A national survey of physicians found that 70% felt that reviewing information in the EHR took more time.<sup><a href="#r21-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r21-2976958">21</a></sup> Two qualitative studies interviewing physicians also highlighted that one major challenge for physicians was managing the amount of information available in the EHR, even for experienced physicians.<sup><a href="#r22-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r22-2976958">22</a>,<a href="#r23-2976958" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r23-2976958">23</a></sup> Our findings support the idea that providers spend a significant amount of time in the EHR reviewing information, and suggests more focus should be placed on understanding and reforming how providers review information in the EHR.</p>
<p>This study had several limitations. First, the validation of our methodology consisted of self-reported data from one provider. Since we are most interested in capturing EHR usage that occurs outside of clinic, self-reported data seems the most practical method for collecting validation data. However, future studies should use multiple providers from different specialties to ensure a more robust validation. Second, our validation did not confirm our estimation of various subcategories of EHR activity were accurate estimations, indeed our findings suggest we are severely underestimating the amount of time spent on certain activities in the EHR. Third, when relevant timestamps for encounters were missing, an approximate timestamp was substituted instead. These approximations may be too conservative or too generous, and may therefor effect the amount of time spent on each kind of <em>Patient Care.</em> Future studies more interested in specific kinds of <em>Patient Care</em> may wish to be more selective in their exclusion criteria.</p></section><section id="sec5"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Conclusion</h2>
<p>These study findings support the notion that providers spend extensive time using the electronic health record. This study provides a methodological tool to evaluate EHR usage using secondary data, identifies specifics areas where ophthalmologists spend most time using the EHR, and highlights potential areas where changes in the EHR may be warranted. These study findings have important implications for practicing clinicians regarding workflow and quality of life, and for informaticians regarding EHR usability and system design.</p></section><section id="ack1" class="ack"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Acknowledgements</h2>
<p>Supported by grants T15LM007088, K99LM012238, and P30EY0105072 from the National Institutes of Health, (Bethesda, MD) and unrestricted departmental support from Research to Prevent Blindness (New York, NY).</p></section><section id="ref-list1" class="ref-list"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">References</h2>
